nformed by research into the archival documentary record on Iraqis in North America, this book is first and foremost a study of gender and memory that focuses on women’s oral histories. By historicizing the process through which ethno-religious and ethno-national communities become fractured and remade, Jones-Gailani explores the expectations and realities of women as the supposed biological and cultural reproducers of the nation. The Iraqi women featured in this book assert their claims to belonging across three different generations, thereby opening up spaces to discuss how sites of migration shape the ability of migrants to lobby for "the homeland," even as they engage in daily struggles to advance their education and economic stability abroad.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBelonging (Social psychology). 0aGroup identity. 0aIraqisxMigrations. 0aIraqiszJordanzAmmanxEthnic identity. 0aIraqiszJordanzAmmanxSocial life and customs. 0aIraqiszMichiganzDetroitxEthnic identity. 0aIraqiszMichiganzDetroitxSocial life and customs. 0aIraqiszOntariozTorontoxEthnic identity. 0aIraqiszOntariozTorontoxSocial life and customs. 0aWomenzIraqvBiography. 7aHISTORY / North America.2bisacsh  aAmman.  aDetroit.  aIraqi diaspora.  aToronto.  aaffective.  acounter-narratives.  aethnicity.  afeminism.  agender.  ahomeland.  aidentity.  aimmigration.  amemory.  amigration.  amulticulturalism.  aoral history.  atransnational.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751731140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517311423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487517311.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete 